        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Greensboro, NC: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Greensboro, NC, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Greensboro Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the NC Fire Code (IFC-based) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Greensboro Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Greensboro enforces the NC Fire Code (IFC-based), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10</a>. Greensboro is the Triad region's largest city and seat of Guilford County. The commercial landscape spans the revitalized Downtown entertainment and restaurant corridor, the South Elm Street arts district, Greensboro Coliseum complex, significant manufacturing and distribution facilities, and the growing Four Seasons Town Centre retail area. Greensboro's manufacturing sector — textiles, logistics, and industrial operations — creates specific Class B and Class C extinguisher requirements beyond standard commercial.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff. Verify each unit is in place, unobstructed, pressure gauge reads in the operating range, tamper seal is intact, and pull pin is present. Document every check — absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician. North Carolina requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold licensing under NC law administered by the NC Office of State Fire Marshal (919-661-5880) through the NC Fire Protection Contractor Licensing Board. Verify your provider holds current NC credentials before scheduling service. The technician inspects all components and attaches a dated service tag. Failed units must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination & 12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure units must be internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. At 12 years, cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing — units that fail are condemned. Your service provider should track these intervals based on each unit's manufacture date.</p>
